        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "My Bosch washer door won't lock or unlock — E02 or E03 code",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Door lock assembly failure — the single most common non-drain service call on Bosch compact washers. E02 means door failed to unlock at end of cycle; E03 means door failed to lock at start. Diagnostic: test door lock resistance with multimeter — should read 159-211 ohms across the lock coil terminals. Reading outside this range means the lock coil has degraded, replacement needed. $195-$285 door lock assembly replacement, 45-minute job. Before replacing: try a 5-minute power cycle (unplug, wait, plug back in) — about 10% of door lock codes are transient control-board glitches that clear on reset. If door is locked with clothes inside, there's a manual emergency release tab near the drain pump filter access panel at the bottom-front of the washer."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Bosch washer won't drain — E13, E18, or E23",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "All three are drainage-related but point to different components. E13 = drain pump taking too long (can also indicate door lock fault after successful drain — confusing dual-meaning code). E18 = drain pipe blocked or drain hose installed too high (must be max 39 inches / 1 meter above floor per Bosch spec). E23 = water detected in base pan (leak indicator). Diagnostic order: (1) clean drain pump filter at bottom-front access panel — catches coins, hair, lint, fabric; 70% of E13/E18 calls resolve here free. (2) Inspect drain hose for kinks or mounting too high. (3) Test drain pump electrically — if pump hums but doesn't drain, impeller blocked ($165-$245 pump). (4) Check water-level pressure switch if pump tests good ($125-$185). (5) For E23 specifically, identify leak source (pump seal, door gasket, water inlet valve) before resetting the sensor."
