        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Same 24-inch compact chassis with progressive feature tiers. 300 Series (WAT prefix) — basic wash programs, standard spin speed, simple electronic controls, no WiFi. 500 Series — additional cycles including Allergen and Sanitize, higher max spin (1400 RPM), improved vibration dampening, Home Connect WiFi on 2020+. 800 Series (WAW prefix) — maximum 1400-1600 RPM spin, all cycle options, Home Connect standard, AntiVibration sides, EcoSilence motor system. Service parts largely shared: same door lock mechanism, same drain pump family, same shock absorber design across tiers. Main service difference is the motor — 800 Series uses EcoSilence direct-drive motor with no carbon brushes (no F21 brush-wear failures), while 300/500 use brushed motors that need brush replacement around year 6-8."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "My Bosch washer is shaking violently during spin",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Shock absorber failure or unbalanced load. Diagnostic: (1) First check — is the load unbalanced? Single heavy item (bathmat, comforter) on one side of the drum is the #1 cause of violent spin shake, redistribute load and try again (free fix). (2) Check shipping bolts — if the washer was recently moved, the rear shipping bolts must be removed before use; leaving them installed causes immediate and severe vibration. (3) Shock absorber wear — Bosch uses 4 shock absorbers (two front, two rear) that dampen drum oscillation during spin. After 8-10 years, absorbers lose dampening capacity. We replace as a complete 4-piece set ($385-$540) rather than individual absorbers — mixing worn and new absorbers creates diagonal imbalance. (4) Suspension spring failure — rare but occurs on 12+ year units, additional $245-$345 per spring."
